    "> why not use> \n> \nPath finding library for Rust> \nThis crate implements several pathfinding, flow, and graph algorithms in Rust.> \n> \nAlgorithms> \nThe algorithms are generic over their arguments.> \n> \nDirected graphs> \nA*: find the shortest path in a weighted graph using an heuristic to guide the process.> \nBFS: explore nearest successors first, then widen the search.> \nBrent: find a cycle in an infinite sequence.> \nDFS: explore a graph by going as far as possible, then backtrack.> \nDijkstra: find the shortest path in a weighted graph.> \nEdmonds Karp: find the maximum flow in a weighted graph.> \nFloyd: find a cycle in an infinite sequence.> \nFringe: find the shortest path in a weighted graph using an heuristic to guide the process.> \nIDA*: explore longer and longer paths in a weighted graph at the cost of multiple similar examinations.> \nIDDFS: explore longer and longer paths in an unweighted graph at the cost of multiple similar examinations.> \nstrongly connected components: find strongly connected components in a directed graph.> \ntopological sorting: find an acceptable topological order in a directed graph.> \nYen: find k-shortest paths using Dijkstra.> \nUndirected graphs> \nconnected components: find disjoint connected sets of vertices.> \nKruskal: find a minimum-spanning-tree.> \nMatching> \nKuhn-Munkres (Hungarian algorithm): find the maximum (or minimum) matching in a weighted bipartite graph.> \nMiscellaneous structures> \nA Grid type representing a rectangular grid in which vertices can be added or removed, with automatic creation of edges between adjacent vertices.> \nA Matrix type to store data of arbitrary types, with neighbour-aware methods.> \nUsing pathfinding> \nIn order to use pathfinding, you can add it to your Cargo.toml as a dependency> \n[dependencies]> \npathfinding = \"4.8\"> \nThe package documentation is available online.> \nGetting pathfinding> \nPublished version (4.8)> \n> \npathfinding::directed> \nModule astar Copy item path> \nSource> \nSearch> \nSettings> \nHelp> \n> \nSummary> \nCompute a shortest path (or all shorted paths) using the A* search algorithm.> \n> \nStructs> \nAstarSolution> \nIterator structure created by the astar_bag function.> \nFunctions> \nastar> \nCompute a shortest path using the A* search algorithm.> \nastar_bag> \nCompute all shortest paths using the A* search algorithm.> \nastar_bag_collect> \nCompute all shortest paths using the A* search algorithm.",
    "Great idea! Let's use the `pathfinding` crate for the elbow arrow routing. This will be much cleaner than implementing A* from scratch.\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now let's create an elbow routing module. The idea is: for Angular path style, we compute the elbow path using A* on a grid:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now add the module to lib.rs and use it in the Arrow's to_path for Angular mode:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now update Arrow's `to_path` to use elbow routing for Angular mode:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see that Angular currently just draws straight lines through points. For elbow arrows, we need to compute the elbow path dynamically when there are no intermediate points, or use the existing points if they exist. Let me update the Arrow's to_path:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now I need to remove the duplicate arrowhead code that was left after the replacement. Let me check:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "There's duplicate code. Let me fix it:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Tool uses were interrupted, waiting for the next user prompt\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I want you to implement astar base search similar to original, we can use a create like> \n> \npub fn astar<N, C, FN, IN, FH, FS>(> \n    start: &N,> \n    successors: FN,> \n    heuristic: FH,> \n    success: FS,> \n) -> Option<(Vec<N>, C)>where> \n    N: Eq + Hash + Clone,> \n    C: Zero + Ord + Copy,> \n    FN: FnMut(&N) -> IN,> \n    IN: IntoIterator<Item = (N, C)>,> \n    FH: FnMut(&N) -> C,> \n    FS: FnMut(&N) -> bool,Expand descriptionCompute a shortest path using the A* search> \nalgorithm.> \nThe shortest path starting from start up to a node for which success returns true is> \ncomputed and returned along with its total cost, in a Some. If no path can be found, None> \nis returned instead.> \n> \nstart is the starting node.> \nsuccessors returns a list of successors for a given node, along with the cost for moving> \nfrom the node to the successor. This cost must be non-negative.> \nheuristic returns an approximation of the cost from a given node to the goal. The> \napproximation must not be greater than the real cost, or a wrong shortest path may be returned.> \nsuccess checks whether the goal has been reached. It is not a node as some problems require> \na dynamic solution instead of a fixed node.> \n> \nA node will never be included twice in the path as determined by the Eq relationship.> \nThe returned path comprises both the start and end node.> \n§Example> \nWe will search the shortest path on a chess board to go from (1, 1) to (4, 6) doing only knight> \nmoves.> \nThe first version uses an explicit type Pos on which the required traits are derived.> \n> \nuse pathfinding::prelude::astar;> \n> \n#[derive(Clone, Debug, Eq, Hash, Ord, PartialEq, PartialOrd)]> \nstruct Pos(i32, i32);> \n> \nimpl Pos {> \n  fn distance(&self, other: &Pos) -> u32 {> \n    (self.0.abs_diff(other.0) + self.1.abs_diff(other.1)) as u32> \n  }> \n> \n  fn successors(&self) -> Vec<(Pos, u32)> {> \n    let &Pos(x, y) = self;> \n    vec![Pos(x+1,y+2), Pos(x+1,y-2), Pos(x-1,y+2), Pos(x-1,y-2),> \n         Pos(x+2,y+1), Pos(x+2,y-1), Pos(x-2,y+1), Pos(x-2,y-1)]> \n         .into_iter().map(|p| (p, 1)).collect()> \n  }> \n}> \n> \nstatic GOAL: Pos = Pos(4, 6);> \nlet result = astar(&Pos(1, 1), |p| p.successors(), |p| p.distance(&GOAL) / 3,> \n                   |p| *p == GOAL);> \nassert_eq!(result.expect(\"no path found\").1, 4);> \nThe second version does not declare a Pos type, makes use of more closures,> \nand is thus shorter.> \n> \nuse pathfinding::prelude::astar;> \n> \nstatic GOAL: (i32, i32) = (4, 6);> \nlet result = astar(&(1, 1),> \n                   |&(x, y)| vec![(x+1,y+2), (x+1,y-2), (x-1,y+2), (x-1,y-2),> \n                                  (x+2,y+1), (x+2,y-1), (x-2,y+1), (x-2,y-1)]> \n                              .into_iter().map(|p| (p, 1)),> \n                   |&(x, y)| (GOAL.0.abs_diff(x) + GOAL.1.abs_diff(y)) / 3,> \n                   |&p| p == GOAL);> \nassert_eq!(result.expect(\"no path found\").1, 4);",
    "Let me rewrite the elbow routing to properly use A* like Excalidraw does - with a grid-based approach that only allows orthogonal movement:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "It compiles. Now let me also update Line to use elbow routing for Angular mode:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done! Here's a summary of the elbow arrow implementation:\n\n**Added `pathfinding` crate** to Cargo.toml\n\n**Created `elbow.rs` module** with A* pathfinding:\n- Uses grid-based pathfinding with orthogonal moves only (up/down/left/right)\n- `Pos` struct with `successors()` returning 4 orthogonal neighbors\n- Manhattan distance heuristic\n- `compute_elbow_path(start, end)` returns intermediate corner points\n- `simplify_path()` extracts only corner points where direction changes\n- Falls back to simple L-shape if A* fails\n\n**Updated `Line::to_path()` and `Arrow::to_path()`**:\n- For `PathStyle::Angular` with no intermediate points, dynamically computes elbow path using A*\n- If intermediate points exist (e.g., from Excalidraw import or user edits), uses those directly\n- Arrow's arrowhead direction is computed from the last segment for correct orientation\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> it behaves differently than the original",
    "Let me look more carefully at how Excalidraw's elbow arrows actually work:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "I see - Excalidraw elbow arrows have a specific pattern: they go horizontal first, then vertical, then horizontal again (or vice versa). It's not A* pathfinding - it's a simple geometric calculation. Let me look at more examples:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "> it is both, look at the code!",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see! The key differences in Excalidraw's A* implementation:\n\n1. **Direction change penalty** - `bendMultiplier` penalizes turns heavily (`Math.pow(bendMultiplier, 3)`)\n2. **No reverse movement** - can't go backwards\n3. **Start/end headings** - respects the direction the arrow should leave/enter\n4. **Estimated bend count** in heuristic\n\nLet me rewrite the elbow module to match this behavior:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "The key changes to match Excalidraw's behavior:\n\n1. **State includes direction** - tracks which direction we came from\n2. **No reverse movement** - can't go back the way we came\n3. **Heavy turn penalty** - `bend_cost * bend_cost` for direction changes (like Excalidraw's `bendMultiplier^3`)\n4. **Heuristic includes turn estimate** - adds penalty for expected turns\n5. **Initial heading** - starts in the direction of the longer axis (horizontal or vertical)\n\nThis should produce paths that prefer straight lines and minimize turns, just like Excalidraw.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> why do we need a fallback?",
    "You're right - with A* on an unbounded grid with orthogonal moves, there's always a path between any two points. The fallback is unnecessary.\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done. Removed the fallback and simplified the code. A* on an unbounded orthogonal grid will always find a path.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> do we have same costs function?",
    "Let me compare the cost functions:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now let me check what `bendMultiplier` and `m_dist` are:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now I understand. Excalidraw's costs:\n- `bendMultiplier = manhattan_distance(start, end)` \n- **g score**: `m_dist(neighbor, current) + (directionChange ? bendMultiplier^3 : 0)`\n- **h score**: `m_dist(end, neighbor) + estBendCount * bendMultiplier^2`\n\nMy implementation uses `bend_cost^2` for turns, but Excalidraw uses `bendMultiplier^3`. Let me fix this:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Now the cost functions match Excalidraw:\n\n| | Excalidraw | Our implementation |\n|---|---|---|\n| **bendMultiplier** | `m_dist(start, end)` | `m_dist(sx, sy, ex, ey)` |\n| **g score (move)** | `m_dist(neighbor, current)` | `1` (grid step) |\n| **g score (turn)** | `+ bendMultiplier^3` | `+ bend_multiplier.pow(3)` |\n| **h score (dist)** | `m_dist(end, neighbor)` | `m_dist(state, end)` |\n| **h score (turns)** | `+ estBendCount * bendMultiplier^2` | `+ est_bends * bend_multiplier.pow(2)` |\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> we have 1 bend, but exaclidraw has the nice 2 bends at least which is vusally more pleasing, from start in target dir, then ... and JUST see youself how it is using astar",
    "You're right! Looking at Excalidraw's elbow arrows, they typically have 2 bends - they go out from the start in a direction, then turn, then turn again to reach the end. Let me look at how they handle the start/end \"dongles\":\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see! Excalidraw uses \"dongles\" - offset points from start/end. The A* runs between the dongles, then the actual start/end points are added. This creates the 2-bend pattern:\n\n`start → startDongle → ... A* path ... → endDongle → end`\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Now the elbow routing works like Excalidraw:\n\n1. **Dongle points** - offset 40px from start/end in their heading direction\n2. **A* runs between dongles** - finds optimal path with turn penalties\n3. **Result**: `start → startDongle → [A* corners] → endDongle → end`\n\nThis creates the visually pleasing 2+ bend pattern:\n```\nstart ──→ startDongle\n                │\n                ↓ (A* path with minimal turns)\n                │\n          endDongle ←── end\n```\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> we should make up name names for these concepts. do not use dongles for example",
    "Good point! Let me rename with clearer, more descriptive names:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Renamed concepts:\n\n| Old | New |\n|-----|-----|\n| `dongle` | `departure` / `arrival` (waypoints) |\n| `Dir` | `Heading` (cardinal direction) |\n| `State` | `Cell` (grid cell with heading) |\n| `opposite()` | `reverse()` |\n| `m_dist` | `manhattan` |\n| `bend_multiplier` | `turn_penalty` |\n| `simplify_path` | `extract_corners` |\n| `successors` | `neighbors` |\n| `heuristic` | `estimate` |\n| `DONGLE_OFFSET` | `WAYPOINT_DISTANCE` |\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> something is off, it should prefer dongle at correct orientatin. ours is wrong the final dongle is on wrong side",
    "You're right - the arrival waypoint should be on the side where the arrow approaches from, not the opposite. Let me fix the arrival heading logic:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Now the arrival waypoint is placed correctly - it's offset from the end point in the opposite direction of approach, so the arrow arrives cleanly:\n\n```\nFor start→end going right and down:\n\nstart ──→ departure\n               │\n               ↓\n          arrival ──→ end\n```\n\nThe arrival waypoint is now to the LEFT of end (subtracting the right offset), so the final segment goes left-to-right into the end point.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> departure and arrival probably have minimal size in exaclidraw",
    "Let me check Excalidraw's BASE_PADDING and how they handle the dongle distance:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "I see - `BASE_PADDING = 40` is correct. But they also check if the segment is too short (`segmentLength < BASE_PADDING + 5`). The waypoint distance should be at least some minimum but could be adjusted. Our 40.0 matches Excalidraw's BASE_PADDING.\n\nHowever, looking at the code, they seem to use the same BASE_PADDING (40) consistently. The issue might be elsewhere. Let me check if there's any minimum distance logic:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see - when the segment is too short, they use `segmentLength / 2` instead of `BASE_PADDING`. This prevents the waypoints from overshooting when start and end are close together. Let me add this logic:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
