    "Good, the offset method already takes a distance parameter. Now let me update compute_elbow_path to use compute_waypoint_distance:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see the offset() calls don't have the distance parameter. Let me fix that:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done. Now the waypoint distance adapts:\n- Normal case: `WAYPOINT_DISTANCE` (40px)\n- When points are close (`< 90px`): `distance / 4` (minimum 10px)\n\nThis prevents waypoints from overshooting when start and end are near each other.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> departure and arrival looks more consistent in exaclidraw (they seem to have same size)",
    "You're right - in Excalidraw both departure and arrival segments have the same length (BASE_PADDING = 40). Let me simplify and just use the constant:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
