    "> check orignal impl",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see! Excalidraw's `getDonglePosition` uses **bounds** not a fixed offset. The dongle is placed at the edge of the element's bounding box. Since we don't have element bounds (just start/end points), we use a fixed offset.\n\nBut the key insight is they use the same logic for both start and end - just with different bounds and headings. Let me check how they compute the bounds:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see - they use `dynamicAABBs` which are bounding boxes around the start/end elements. Since we don't have element bindings, our fixed offset approach is correct. The key is that both use the same `BASE_PADDING` (40).\n\nLet me verify our code compiles and the logic is sound:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "It compiles. Our implementation now:\n\n1. Uses `WAYPOINT_DISTANCE = 40.0` (same as Excalidraw's `BASE_PADDING`)\n2. Computes a dynamic distance when points are close (to avoid overshooting)\n3. Uses the **same distance** for both departure and arrival waypoints\n4. The A* pathfinding runs between the waypoints with turn penalties\n\nThe main difference from Excalidraw is they use element bounding boxes for waypoint placement (for element-to-element connections), while we use a fixed offset since we only have point-to-point connections.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> /compact",
    "> check orignal impl ours has bad end arrival (they call it dongle)",
    "Let me check Excalidraw's dongle implementation more closely, particularly for the arrival/end dongle positioning.\n[Tool uses: web_fetch]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Now I see the key insight. The `getDonglePosition` function uses the **bounds** to position the dongle, not a fixed offset. Let me check what `dynamicAABBs` are:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Now I understand! The key insight is:\n\n**Excalidraw's `getDonglePosition`** uses the **bounds edge** based on heading:\n- `HEADING_UP`: dongle at `(p.x, bounds[1])` - top edge of bounds\n- `HEADING_RIGHT`: dongle at `(bounds[2], p.y)` - right edge of bounds  \n- `HEADING_DOWN`: dongle at `(p.x, bounds[3])` - bottom edge of bounds\n- `HEADING_LEFT`: dongle at `(bounds[0], p.y)` - left edge of bounds\n\nThe `dynamicAABBs` are expanded bounding boxes around each endpoint. The dongle is placed at the **edge of this expanded bounding box** in the direction of the heading.\n\nLet me check our current implementation:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see the issue. Our arrival waypoint calculation is wrong:\n\n```rust\nlet arrival = Point::new(end.x - arr_offset.0, end.y - arr_offset.1);\n```\n\nWe're subtracting the offset, but the arrival heading represents the direction we're **arriving from**, not the direction to the end. The dongle should be positioned so the path arrives at the end from the correct direction.\n\nLooking at Excalidraw's `getDonglePosition`:\n- For `HEADING_RIGHT` arrival: dongle at `(bounds[2], p.y)` - to the **right** of the endpoint\n- This means the path goes TO the dongle, then FROM dongle to endpoint (going left)\n\nOur issue: we compute `arrival_heading` as the direction from start to end, but we should be computing where the dongle sits relative to the endpoint based on the **incoming** direction.\n\nLet me fix this:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Compiles. But wait - I need to reconsider the logic. Looking at Excalidraw again:\n\nThe `arrival_heading` represents the direction the arrow is **heading toward** the endpoint. So if `arrival_heading = HEADING_RIGHT`, the arrow is moving right toward the end. The dongle should be placed so the final segment goes in that direction.\n\nActually, let me re-read Excalidraw's logic more carefully:\n\n```typescript\nconst getDonglePosition = (bounds, heading, p) => {\n  switch (heading) {\n    case HEADING_UP:    return pointFrom(p[0], bounds[1]);  // dongle above\n    case HEADING_RIGHT: return pointFrom(bounds[2], p[1]); // dongle to right\n    case HEADING_DOWN:  return pointFrom(p[0], bounds[3]); // dongle below\n  }\n  return pointFrom(bounds[0], p[1]); // HEADING_LEFT: dongle to left\n};\n```\n\nSo if `endHeading = HEADING_RIGHT`, the dongle is placed to the **right** of the endpoint. This means the path goes TO the dongle (which is right of end), then the final segment goes LEFT from dongle to endpoint.\n\nBut that seems backwards... Let me check how `endHeading` is computed:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "The key line is:\n```typescript\nconst otherPointHeading = vectorToHeading(vectorFromPoint(otherPoint, p));\n```\n\nSo when there's no bound element, `endHeading` is the heading from `endPoint` toward `startPoint`. This is the **opposite** of what I thought!\n\nFor `endHeading`:\n- `p = endGlobalPoint`\n- `otherPoint = startGlobalPoint`\n- `vectorFromPoint(startPoint, endPoint)` = direction from end toward start\n\nSo `endHeading` is the direction the arrow is **coming from** (pointing back toward start), not the direction it's going.\n\nThis means:\n- If `endHeading = HEADING_RIGHT`, the start is to the RIGHT of the end\n- The dongle is placed at `(bounds[2], p.y)` = to the right of end\n- The path goes to the dongle, then LEFT from dongle to endpoint\n\nThis makes sense! The dongle is placed in the direction of the incoming path.\n\nNow let me re-check our code. Our `arrival_heading` is computed as the direction from start to end (the direction the arrow is traveling). So it's the **opposite** of Excalidraw's `endHeading`.\n\nSo if our `arrival_heading = HEADING_RIGHT` (arrow going right), Excalidraw's `endHeading = HEADING_LEFT` (arrow coming from left).\n\nExcalidraw places dongle at `bounds[0]` (left edge) for `HEADING_LEFT`.\n\nSo for our `arrival_heading = HEADING_RIGHT`, we should place the arrival dongle to the **left** of the endpoint (opposite of arrival direction), so the final segment goes right.\n\nMy fix using `arrival_heading.reverse()` should be correct! Let me verify the logic:\n\n- `arrival_heading = HEADING_RIGHT` (arrow going right toward end)\n- `arrival_heading.reverse() = HEADING_LEFT`\n- `HEADING_LEFT.offset(wp_dist) = (-wp_dist, 0)`\n- `arrival = Point::new(end.x - wp_dist, end.y)` - dongle to the LEFT of end\n\nThen the path goes to this dongle, and the final segment goes RIGHT from dongle to end. ✓\n\nLet me double-check the current code:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "The fix looks correct. Let me run a quick test to verify the behavior:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Build succeeded. The fix changes the arrival dongle position from:\n- **Before**: `end.x - arr_offset.0` (subtracting the offset in arrival direction)\n- **After**: `end.x + reverse_arr_offset.0` (adding the offset in the opposite direction)\n\nThis places the arrival dongle on the side the path is coming FROM, so the final segment goes in the correct direction toward the endpoint - matching Excalidraw's behavior.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> /model",
    "> just compare ours /tmp/ours.png and theirs /tmp/theirs.png",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see the difference clearly:\n\n**Ours (top)**: The arrow goes `right → down → right → up → right` - 4 bends, and the final segment goes UP to the arrowhead\n\n**Theirs (bottom)**: The arrow goes `right → up → right` - only 2 bends, and the final segment goes RIGHT to the arrowhead\n\nThe issue is our arrival heading logic. Looking at the endpoints:\n- Start: bottom-left\n- End: top-right\n\nExcalidraw's arrow arrives at the endpoint going **horizontally right**. Ours arrives going **vertically up**.\n\nThe problem is how we compute `arrival_heading`. We're using the same logic as `departure_heading` (based on which axis has larger delta), but Excalidraw seems to prefer the arrival to match the departure direction when possible, creating a cleaner 2-bend path.\n\nLet me check the current logic and fix it:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "The issue is that `arrival_heading` should match `departure_heading` for the cleanest 2-bend path. Excalidraw's elbow arrows try to maintain the same axis for both departure and arrival when possible.\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done. Now the arrival heading matches the departure heading, so for your example:\n- Start: bottom-left, End: top-right\n- `dx > dy`, so `departure_heading = Right`\n- `arrival_heading = Right` (same)\n- Departure dongle: to the right of start\n- Arrival dongle: to the left of end (reverse of Right)\n\nThis should produce a clean 2-bend path: `right → up → right` matching Excalidraw's behavior.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> for me it looks like the end dongle (arrival) is constant and the start dongle depature increase when dragging. i dont see that consistency",
    "Let me look at how Excalidraw computes the dynamic bounds for dongles - they use `dynamicAABBs` which expand based on the distance between points:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "I see - Excalidraw's dongles use **dynamic bounds** that expand to meet in the middle between start and end. The key insight is `(startEl[0] + endEl[2]) / 2` - the bounds extend to the **midpoint** between the two elements.\n\nLet me look at `getDonglePosition` again - it places the dongle at the **edge of the bounds**, not at a fixed offset:\n\n```typescript\nconst getDonglePosition = (bounds, heading, p) => {\n  switch (heading) {\n    case HEADING_UP:    return pointFrom(p[0], bounds[1]);  // top edge\n    case HEADING_RIGHT: return pointFrom(bounds[2], p[1]); // right edge\n    case HEADING_DOWN:  return pointFrom(p[0], bounds[3]); // bottom edge\n  }\n  return pointFrom(bounds[0], p[1]); // left edge\n};\n```\n\nSo the dongle is at the **bounds edge**, and the bounds dynamically expand toward the midpoint. This means both dongles grow proportionally as the distance increases.\n\nOur current implementation uses a fixed `WAYPOINT_DISTANCE` which doesn't scale. Let me fix this:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "The issue is clear now. Excalidraw places dongles at the **midpoint** between start and end (on the relevant axis), not at a fixed offset. Let me rewrite the dongle positioning:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
