    "So the model should be:\n- `Direct` vs `Flowing` = line style (sharp vs smooth)\n- `Angular` = elbow routing mode (orthogonal paths)\n\nWhen Angular is enabled, it computes the elbow path. The line style (Direct/Flowing) would apply to how those segments are rendered.\n\nBut currently Angular is a separate enum variant. We need to split this into two properties:\n1. `line_style: LineStyle` (Direct or Flowing)\n2. `is_angular: bool` (elbow routing)\n\nOr keep it simpler - Angular overrides the path completely with elbow routing, and Direct/Flowing only matter for non-angular paths.\n\nLet me check how Excalidraw handles this - they have \"Arrow type\" with straight/curved/elbow as separate options:\n\nLooking at the Excalidraw UI in your screenshot, they have:\n- Arrow type: straight / curved / elbow (mutually exclusive)\n\nSo actually they ARE mutually exclusive in Excalidraw. But you're saying you want Angular to be a modifier on top?\n\nLet me clarify - do you want:\n1. Two separate toggles: [Direct|Flowing] + [Angular on/off]\n2. Or keep three mutually exclusive options but fix some behavior?\n\nFor now, let me assume you want the current three options to remain mutually exclusive, but the UI/behavior needs fixing. What specifically is broken?\n[Tool uses: none]",
