    "> how is the undo and redo system implemented?",
    "Let me look at the undo/redo implementation in the codebase.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "The undo/redo system is built on top of **Loro's `UndoManager`** - a CRDT (Conflict-free Replicated Data Type) library. Here's how it works:\n\n**Architecture:**\n- `CrdtDocument` wraps a `LoroDoc` and an `UndoManager`\n- The `UndoManager` automatically tracks all changes to the document\n\n**Configuration:**\n- Max 100 undo steps\n- 300ms merge interval - edits within this window are grouped into a single undo step\n\n**API exposed by `CrdtDocument`:**\n- `undo()` / `redo()` - perform the operation, returns `bool` success\n- `can_undo()` / `can_redo()` - check availability\n- `undo_count()` / `redo_count()` - number of available steps\n- `record_checkpoint()` - manually create an undo boundary\n- `start_undo_group()` / `end_undo_group()` - group multiple changes into one undo step\n- `clear_undo_history()` - wipe the history\n\n**Key behavior:**\n- Undo is **per-peer** (local operations only) - important for collaboration\n- Changes are automatically tracked when shapes are added/removed/modified via the CRDT document\n- The merge interval means rapid edits (like dragging a shape) get batched together\n\nThis is a clean delegation pattern - Drafft.ink doesn't implement its own undo stack, it leverages Loro's built-in undo support which is designed to work correctly with CRDTs in collaborative scenarios.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Based on the analysis of `crates/drafftink-core/src/shapes/rectangle.rs`, the `id` field is already marked as `pub(crate)`, which means it is visible to the `crdt` module within the same crate. The original \"Double Serialization\" hack was likely added under the mistaken assumption that `id` was private or to avoid writing explicit constructors.> \n> \nHere is the plan to fix the \"Double Serialization\" issue by adding explicit reconstruction methods and removing the JSON round-trip.> \n> \n### Step 1: Add Reconstruction Methods to Shapes> \n> \nInstead of exposing raw fields or relying on `pub(crate)` access scattered throughout the codebase, we should add dedicated `reconstruct` methods to your shape structs. This clearly signals that these methods are for internal use (loading/syncing) where the ID is pre-determined.> \n> \n**File:** `crates/drafftink-core/src/shapes/rectangle.rs`> \n> \n```rust> \nimpl Rectangle {> \n    // ... existing new() ...> \n> \n    /// Internal constructor for CRDT/Storage reconstruction.> \n    pub(crate) fn reconstruct(> \n        id: ShapeId, > \n        position: Point, > \n        width: f64, > \n        height: f64, > \n        corner_radius: f64, > \n        style: ShapeStyle> \n    ) -> Self {> \n        Self {> \n            id,> \n            position,> \n            width,> \n            height,> \n            corner_radius,> \n            style,> \n        }> \n    }> \n}> \n> \n```> \n> \n*Repeat this pattern for `Ellipse`, `Line`, `Arrow`, `Freehand`, `Text`, `Group`, and `Image` in their respective files.*> \n> \n### Step 2: Refactor `convert.rs` to Remove `serde_json`> \n> \nNow, update the conversion logic to use these constructors directly. This removes the memory allocation and parsing overhead of JSON.> \n> \n**File:** `crates/drafftink-core/src/crdt/convert.rs`> \n> \n```rust> \n// ... imports ...> \n> \n// Helper to parse ID once and return Option> \nfn get_id(map: &LoroMapValue) -> Option<Uuid> {> \n    let id_str = get_string(map, KEY_ID)?;> \n    Uuid::parse_str(&id_str).ok()> \n}> \n> \n// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------> \n// Refactored conversion functions> \n// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------> \n> \nfn rectangle_from_loro(map: &LoroMapValue) -> Option<Shape> {> \n    let id = get_id(map)?;> \n    let x = get_double(map, KEY_X)?;> \n    let y = get_double(map, KEY_Y)?;> \n    let width = get_double(map, KEY_WIDTH)?;> \n    let height = get_double(map, KEY_HEIGHT)?;> \n    let corner_radius = get_double(map, KEY_CORNER_RADIUS).unwrap_or(0.0);> \n    let style = style_from_loro(map)?;> \n    > \n    // Direct construction - No JSON, No Allocations> \n    Some(Shape::Rectangle(Rectangle::reconstruct(> \n        id,> \n        Point::new(x, y),> \n        width,> \n        height,> \n        corner_radius,> \n        style> \n    )))> \n}> \n> \nfn ellipse_from_loro(map: &LoroMapValue) -> Option<Shape> {> \n    let id = get_id(map)?;> \n    let center_x = get_double(map, KEY_X)?;> \n    let center_y = get_double(map, KEY_Y)?;> \n    let radius_x = get_double(map, KEY_WIDTH)?;> \n    let radius_y = get_double(map, KEY_HEIGHT)?;> \n    let style = style_from_loro(map)?;> \n    > \n    Some(Shape::Ellipse(Ellipse::reconstruct(> \n        id,> \n        Point::new(center_x, center_y),> \n        radius_x,> \n        radius_y,> \n        style> \n    )))> \n}> \n> \nfn line_from_loro(map: &LoroMapValue) -> Option<Shape> {> \n    let id = get_id(map)?;> \n    let start_x = get_double(map, KEY_START_X)?;> \n    let start_y = get_double(map, KEY_START_Y)?;> \n    let end_x = get_double(map, KEY_END_X)?;> \n    let end_y = get_double(map, KEY_END_Y)?;> \n    let style = style_from_loro(map)?;> \n    > \n    Some(Shape::Line(Line::reconstruct(> \n        id,> \n        Point::new(start_x, start_y),> \n        Point::new(end_x, end_y),> \n        style> \n    )))> \n}> \n> \nfn freehand_from_loro(map: &LoroMapValue) -> Option<Shape> {> \n    let id = get_id(map)?;> \n    let style = style_from_loro(map)?;> \n    > \n    // Extract points directly into a Vec<Point>> \n    let points: Vec<Point> = if let Some(LoroValue::List(points_list)) = map.get(KEY_POINTS) {> \n        points_list.iter().filter_map(|p| {> \n            if let LoroValue::List(coords) = p {> \n                if coords.len() >= 2 {> \n                    let x = match coords.first()? {> \n                        LoroValue::Double(d) => *d,> \n                        LoroValue::I64(i) => *i as f64,> \n                        _ => return None,> \n                    };> \n                    let y = match coords.get(1)? {> \n                        LoroValue::Double(d) => *d,> \n                        LoroValue::I64(i) => *i as f64,> \n                        _ => return None,> \n                    };> \n                    return Some(Point::new(x, y));> \n                }> \n            }> \n            None> \n        }).collect()> \n    } else {> \n        vec![]> \n    };> \n    > \n    Some(Shape::Freehand(Freehand::reconstruct(> \n        id,> \n        points,> \n        style> \n    )))> \n}> \n> \n// ... Implement text_from_loro, arrow_from_loro, group_from_loro similarly ...> \n> \n```> \n> \n### Benefits of this Fix> \n> \n1. **Performance:** Removes serialization (Struct -> JSON) and deserialization (JSON -> Struct) steps. Construction becomes an  memory copy.> \n2. **Safety:** `Uuid::parse_str` is handled explicitly, preventing invalid IDs from creating broken shapes.> \n3. **Code Clarity:** The `reconstruct` method documents that the ID is being restored from persistence, distinguishing it from `new()` which generates fresh identity.",
